Malaysia.act:
Personal Data Protection Act (Act 709) 2010;

Personal Data Protection
(Amendment) Bill (Act A1727) 2024

Malaysia.impact:
The Personal Data Protection Act (Act 709) 2010 (PDPA) does not permit a data user to transfer any personal data out of Malaysia. However, the Act offers a set of exceptions, permitting the transfer of data abroad under certain conditions. Section 129 (Cross-border data transfers) prescribes that personal data shall be transferred to any location outside Malaysia if:
- the data subject has given his explicit consent to the transfer; 
- the transfer is necessary for the performance of a contract between the data subject and the data user; 
- the transfer is necessary for the conclusion or performance of a contract between the data user and a third party that is either entered into at the request of the data subject or in his interest; 
- the transfer is in the exercise of or to defend a legal right; 
- the transfer mitigates adverse actions against the data subjects; 
- reasonable precautions and all due diligence to ensure compliance to conditions of the Act were taken; or 
- the transfer was necessary for the protection the data subject’s vital interests or for the public interest as determined by the Minister.

Additionally, Section 6 – General Principle: Personal data shall not be processed unless the data subject consents to the processing, except in specific situations like fulfilling contractual obligations or complying with legal requirements. Section 9 – Security Principle: Data users must take practical steps to ensure personal data is protected against loss, misuse, modification, unauthorized access, or disclosure. This includes securing local processing and storage systems.

The Personal Data Protection (Amendment) Bill 2024 (Act A1727) amendments to the PDPA introduce stricter controls on cross-border data transfers, requiring organizations to assess the recipient country’s data protection framework to ensure that adequate protections are in place before transferring data. This could further encourage local data storage as an easier compliance path. 

- In the Retention Principle (Section 3.1.5), Personal data should not be kept longer than necessary for the purpose it was collected. 
- In the Transfer of Personal Data Abroad, Section 4.11 prohibits the transfer of personal data abroad unless the recipient country ensures adequate protection under similar data protection laws or explicit consent from the data subject is obtained.
- In the Conditions for Transfer in Schedule 1, Section 1.1(38): Any cross-border transfer must ensure compliance with the PDPA’s principles, particularly related to the security of data, and must have written agreements with third-party data processors abroad.

