Personal Data Protection Standard 2015

Malaysia.impact:
The data retention requirements for personal data are generally governed by the Personal Data Protection Act (Act 709) 2010 (PDPA). The PDPA 2010 enforces the Retention Principle, which requires data to be kept only as long as necessary for the purpose for which it was collected. However, this principle allows individual sectors to set their own retention periods based on operational needs or other regulatory obligations. In addition to the retention principle under the PDPA, the 2015 Standards outline the main standards for data retention which apply to personal data which is processed either electronically or non-electronically. A brief overview of the measures prescribed by the 2015 Standards are as follows:
1) to ensure that all legislation relating to the processing and storing of personal data is complied with before disposing of personal data;
2) not retaining personal data for longer than is required unless there are other legislative requirements that require personal data to be kept for a longer period;
3) to prepare and maintain records on the disposal of personal data and to submit these records when directed by the Commissioner;
4) to dispose of any personal data collection forms used for commercial transactions within 14 days, unless the form has legislative value in connection with the commercial transaction;
5) to review and dispose of all personal data that is no longer needed in the database;
6) to have a personal data disposal schedule for a period of 24 months for any inactive personal data; and
to obtain written consent from the higher management of the data user's organization if using removable media devices for the purposes of personal data storage.

